abstract = {Current power systems are rapidly changing and becoming more challenging with the increasing penetration of distributed energy resources, renewable energy resources, and distributed generation. This makes the future power system highly stochastic; thus, its control on both the source and demand side becomes exceptionally challenging. Therefore, the future power system must be flexible and have enough capacity to sustain this intermittency reliably. There is a need for a survey that analyzes the flexibility concept in detail and discusses how to enable demand-side flexibility through demand-side management and demand response programs. This review paper presents a comprehensive overview of the concepts, modeling, and provision methods related to flexibility in smart grids. Furthermore, it models and studies the various demand-side flexible resources that may be deployed in the flexibility provision. It examines and categorizes flexibility services and resources while considering their key characteristics, such as their scope, purpose, location, and describes some key strategies for designing and implementing flexibility markets. Moreover, it helps formulate mathematical models for flexibility and flexibility provision in smart grids. A brief state-of-the-art review of real-time flexibility by implementing peer-to-peer energy trading in the flexibility framework is provided. The formulation of flexibility and flexibility provided in the distribution system are discussed, and the results are presented. Besides this, the challenges and limitations in flexibility framework and management are explained. Finally, future research directions are suggested to improve the flexibility provision and provide a framework for smart grids.}
