author = {Saumendra Sarangi and Monalisa Biswal},
keywords = {Outage management, Distribution system, Restoration, Renewables, Uninterrupted power supply},
abstract = {Distribution networks (DNs) for electricity are extremely intricate, and their wiring diagrams look like a spider web. Further, additions of renewable into such a DN have converted the network into a dynamic multienergy system. Hence, maintaining coordination of protection relay during a fault in a complex and renewable penetrated grid is a challenge and often it may be lost. As a result, a power outage in a large area following a relay and protective device maloperation is inevitable. Extreme environmental conditions such as storms and hurricanes, and other issues like cyberattack on smart grids are the major issues that can cause large power outages. However, earlier power restoration is essential to get people back to normal in most urban areas after the occurrence of any disaster or power failure following a fault. With the smart grid initiative, many sensors, smart meters, and fault recorders are added for proper monitoring and to capture the parameter variations during disturbances. This has increased the ability of the grid to maintain the desirable parameters within the operating limit of the distribution system (DS). Following an outage in a large area, with signals received from large sets of smart meters, fault indicators, relays, and sensor data, it is merely difficult to search the faulty section to initiate the process of power restoration of the healthy section within a minimum time. Hence, effective outage management is crucial to minimize the impact of power outages in terms of outage time, economic loss, and reliability improvement. The outage management system (OMS) is used by utilities to manage and respond to power outages efficiently. The OMS is designed to streamline the outage management process, from the detection and reporting of outages to the final restoration of power. However, the smart grid framework incorporates proactive measures, advanced analytics, and intelligent decision-making to expedite the restoration process. With real-time monitoring, analytics and artificial intelligent tools are integrated to minimize the outage time. The intelligent decision-making component focuses on fault isolation, optimal resource allocation, crew scheduling, and coordination with stakeholders.}
}
